        "desc": "A hidden gem near Kirkland Lake formed by glacial eskers - long ridges of sand and gravel deposited at the end of the last Ice Age. The result is a strikingly unusual landscape of forested ridges winding between a chain of pristine lakes. Swimming, hiking, fishing, canoeing, and backcountry camping. One of Ontario Parks' best-kept secrets and a geologically fascinating stop on any Northlander journey through the northeast.",
